1. The chocolate factory

You participate in the development of a factory simulator of modern chocolate with boilers assisted by computer.

The task of the boiler is to maintain a mixture of chocolate and milk, bring it to a boil point and then pass it on to the next phase where it is transformed into chocolate bars.

1.1. Initial problem

Here is the controller class of the boiler of Bonchoco, SA.

Java class of the boiler controller
/**
 * @author bruel (taken from Design Pattern - Head First, O'Reilly, 09/2004)
 *
 */
public class BouilleurChocolat {
	private boolean vide;
	private boolean bouilli;

	public BouilleurChocolat() {
		vide = true;
		bouilli = false;
	}

	public void remplir() {
		if (estVide()) {
			vide = false;
			bouilli = false;
			// remplir le bouilleur du mélange lait/chocolat
		}
	}

	public void vider() {
		if (!estVide() && estBouilli()) {
			// vider le mélange
			vide = true;
		}
	}

	public void bouillir() {
		if (!estVide() && !estBouilli()) {
			// porter le contenu à ébullition
			bouilli = true;
		}
	}

	public boolean estVide() { return vide;}

	public boolean estBouilli() { return bouilli;}
}
QUESTION

  1. What are the attributes vide and bouilli used for (empty and boiled) ?
Solution

To control the behavior of the boiler.

    Excerpt of a solution
    public class BouilleurSafeChocolat {
	private boolean vide;
	private boolean bouilli;
	private static BouilleurSafeChocolat uniqueInstance;

	private BouilleurSafeChocolat() {
		vide = true;
		bouilli = false;
		}

	public static final BouilleurSafeChocolat getInstance() {
		if (uniqueInstance == null) {
			uniqueInstance = new BouilleurSafeChocolat();
		}
		return uniqueInstance;
	}

Explications :

  1. Thread 1 calls getInstance() and asserts that uniqueInstance is null in line 12

  2. Thread 1 enters block if then is preempted by thread 2 before the execution in line 13

  3. Thread 2 calls getInstance() and asserts that uniqueInstance is null in line 12

  4. Thread 2 enters block if, create a new BouilleurSafeChocolat and store it in uniqueInstance in line 13

  5. Thread 2 returns the reference of BouilleurSafeChocolat in line 15

  6. Thread 2 is preempted by Thread 1

  7. Thread 1 starts again in ligne 13 creating itself a new instance of BouilleurSafeChocolat

  8. Thread 1 returns this new instance in line 15

1.5. Solution to the multithreading problem

You happily remember your early lessons on threads:

QUESTION

  1. Propose a simple solution to this problem.

Il suffit de faire de getInstance() une méthode synchronisée :

public class BouilleurSafeChocolat {
  private boolean vide;
  private boolean bouilli;
  private static BouilleurSafeChocolat uniqueInstance;

  private BouilleurSafeChocolat() {
    vide = true;
    bouilli = false;
  }

  public static synchronized BouilleurSafeChocolat getInstance() {
    if (uniqueInstance == null) {
      uniqueInstance = new BouilleurSafeChocolat();
    }
    return uniqueInstance;
  }

1.6. Damned, the solution has a problem!!

QUESTION

  1. How often will the mechanism put in place be useful?

  2. What do you think of this solution?

  3. Suggest a solution where the instance is created at startup rather than on demand.

  1. Only once, the 1st time the method is called!!

  2. Way too much expensive in computing resources (memory blocks copied, etc.).

  3. Here is an example:

    Loading instanciation
    public class Singleton {
	private static final Singleton uniqueInstance = new Singleton();
	private Singleton() {}
	public static Singleton getInstance() { return uniqueInstance;}
}

    Here the JVM is creating the (unique) instance of the Singleton when the class is loaded.
There may be situations where the cost of synchronization is lower than the cost of creating an instance from the start (for example, memory-intensive).

2. Singleton

Congratulations, you just practiced your second design pattern: Singleton.

Design pattern : Singleton

Singleton garanties that a class as a unique instance and hence provides a global access to this unique instance.

Figure 2. UML model of the Singleton pattern
Figure 3. Quelques exemples de description du patron Singleton

3. Singleton for the adventure game

3.1. Could we combine patterns?

Can we combine the last two patterns seen in TD (Strategy and Singleton)? In fact, behaviors are carried by objects for the algorithm aspect, but there is no reason not to share them among all the objects that "use" this behavior ?!

In most cases these two patterns do not go together at all. This strategy is only recommended in a specific case of use of Strategy: one where behaviors are simple and "static" (no resource consumption for example) and where an association is used:

With an implementation like:

...
vol = new VolerAvecDesAiles();
cri = new Cancan();
c1 = new Colvert(vol,cri);
...

3.2. Let’s apply Singleton on the adventure game?

QUESTION

  1. Make the object instances assigned to each behavior of a Character are unique for each distinct behavior.

  2. Why shouldn’t we use getInstance () in the case of a UML composition (in the constructor of the compound)?

  1. Excerpt of a possible solution:

    `ComportemenEpee.java`excerpt
    public class ComportementEpee implements ComportementArme {

	private final static ComportementEpee uniqueInstance = new ComportementEpee();

	public final static  ComportementEpee getInstance() {
		return uniqueInstance;
	}

    Which could be improved eventually with:

    private ComportementEpee(){

	}
    Chevalier.java excerpt
    public class Chevalier extends Personnage {

	protected Chevalier(String nom) {
		this(nom, ComportementEpee.getInstance(), ComportementACheval.getInstance());
	}
    Calls like compAdequat = new ComportementEpee(); will need to be changed into compAdequat = ComportementEpee.getInstance();

  2. Because in a composition, objects owns their own behavior instances. They are then unique and should not be transmised outside so that the garbage collector will delete them if the owner is deleted.

What is the difference between singleton and a global variable?

Elements of solution:

  • In Java global variables are static references to objects.

  • On demand instanciatino vs. loading-time instanciation.

Test examples:

  • Construct 2 objects Singleton and check they are the same object
